          "body": "Matthew structures chapter 27 around five independent verdicts of Jesus's innocence, every one given by a hostile or neutral witness. Judas, the betrayer, confesses, \"I have sinned by betraying *innocent blood*\" (27:4). Pilate's wife sends word: \"Have nothing to do with that *righteous Man*\" (27:19). Pilate himself declares, \"I am *innocent* of this Man's blood\" (27:24). Even the mockers concede, \"He saved others\" (27:42). And the centurion confesses, \"Truly this was the *Son of God*\" (27:54). Matthew piles up the testimonies because the death must be established as undeserved for the atonement to be substitutionary. He is not a martyr for a cause; He is the innocent bearing the guilty's wages. The forensic structure of the chapter — verdict after verdict of \"not guilty\" — sets the theological ground for Romans 5:8 and 1 Peter 2:22-24."
