          "title": "The cry of dereliction and the torn veil",
          "body": "From noon to 3 p.m. darkness covers the land (27:45). At the ninth hour Jesus cries the opening line of Psalm 22: *Eli, Eli, lama sabachthani — My God, My God, why have You forsaken Me?* (27:46). This is not theatrical despair; it is the most theologically weighty sentence in the chapter. The Son who has known the Father's face from eternity past now experiences judicial abandonment as He bears the wrath due sinners. Reformed theologians (Calvin, Owen, Edwards) read this as penal substitution at its core moment — the Son enduring the *poena damni*, the punishment of separation, on behalf of those He is redeeming. At the moment of His death, the *naos* veil — the curtain separating the Holy Place from the Holy of Holies — is torn *from top to bottom* (27:51). The direction matters: God tears it, not man; access is opened from heaven down. The old covenant restriction is finished. Hebrews 10:19-22 will state explicitly what Matthew narrates: the way into the holy place is opened by the blood of Jesus."
