          "title": "The sealed tomb and the doomed security",
          "body": "The chapter closes with the chief priests and Pharisees doing what Matthew has been showing all along — meticulous, self-defeating effort to control what only God controls (27:62-66). They remember Jesus's resurrection-prediction more accurately than the disciples do. They go to Pilate on the Sabbath (violating the very law they used against Jesus), request a Roman guard, set a seal on the stone, and \"make the grave secure\" (*asphalizo*, used three times in three verses). The repetition is Matthew's prosecutorial irony: the more they secure, the more decisive the resurrection will be. They cannot keep a dead man dead. The sealed and guarded tomb is the perfect apologetic setup for chapter 28 — every accusation of stolen-body theft has been preemptively ruled out by the enemies themselves. The chapter ends in apparent defeat and total silence; Matthew has positioned every detail for the dawn of the third day."
